1
00:00:01,076 --> 00:00:27,539
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sammasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sammasambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sammasambuddhasa

2
00:00:27,519 --> 00:00:32,484
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed and noble, self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,591 --> 00:01:00,817
so uh last month we did uh courage which doesn't actually come up as a separate item in the ten perfections the ten virtues to be perfected uh but i suppose you could fit it into aditana which means the sort of resolute resolution we'll do that another time anyway but it does have a um what we talked about was courage is doing something you know like achieving something

4
00:01:01,304 --> 00:01:03,548
even though it's very difficult one way or the other.

5
00:01:03,768 --> 00:01:09,498
But there's a passive side to courage, which is, of course, patient forbearance.

6
00:01:09,978 --> 00:01:11,501
Now, the Buddha is very big on that.

7
00:01:14,387 --> 00:01:16,411
He encourages us to develop it.

8
00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:17,251
So this is what he says.

9
00:01:17,352 --> 00:01:22,400
Things like patient endurance is the supreme austerity.

10
00:01:23,528 --> 00:01:32,272
Whoever endures abuse, assault and imprisonment without animosity, and who has forbearance as one's strength,

11
00:01:32,454 --> 00:01:36,319
As one's mighty army, I call a brahmin."

12
00:01:36,338 --> 00:01:41,465
So a brahmin, in the Buddha's understanding, is someone who's achieved something.

13
00:01:41,926 --> 00:01:50,896
He was always poking fun at the brahmins who were pretending to be the spiritual leaders of society.

14
00:01:50,995 --> 00:01:52,578
Many of them were a bit corrupt, I think.

15
00:01:52,878 --> 00:01:54,700
I'm sure there were some good ones.

16
00:01:55,691 --> 00:02:03,643
uh he who holds back rising up rising anger like a rolling chariot him i call a real driver

17
00:02:04,129 --> 00:02:06,112
Other people are but holding the reins.

18
00:02:07,233 --> 00:02:13,301
And there's a verse here from the Theragatha, which is the collective verses of the elders.

19
00:02:13,862 --> 00:02:18,770
This is the senior monks, not the nuns.

20
00:02:19,189 --> 00:02:21,513
Forbearance is the highest virtue.

21
00:02:21,573 --> 00:02:24,456
Forbearance is the highest self-control.

22
00:02:24,516 --> 00:02:28,062
Forbearance is the highest happiness.

23
00:02:28,042 --> 00:02:33,431
So there's a lot going on for this virtue of forbearance.

24
00:02:33,932 --> 00:02:40,906
And we look at one or two areas, all those areas where we feel insulted, slandered and all that sort of stuff.

25
00:02:41,667 --> 00:02:45,394
Then there's the hardships and adversities that come to us through life.

26
00:02:46,475 --> 00:02:50,082
And we're, of course, cultivating patience with others.

27
00:02:50,687 --> 00:02:58,156
Then there's this inner bearing with reactivity, letting go of our inner reactions to things.

28
00:02:58,856 --> 00:03:02,039
And finally, patience with the spiritual path.

29
00:03:03,662 --> 00:03:07,126
And in so doing, we sort of build up this inner strength and resilience.

30
00:03:08,046 --> 00:03:11,389
You know, when everything falls apart, there's that ability to bounce back.

31
00:03:13,812 --> 00:03:19,699
So the first one, just in dealing with insults, criticism, slander,

32
00:03:21,872 --> 00:03:28,681
So it's important for us to face these things when they come up, instead of retaliating, becoming upset.

33
00:03:29,002 --> 00:03:35,949
See, you have to develop this patience and maintain equanimity, which is difficult, of course.

34
00:03:36,531 --> 00:03:42,138
I mean, often the best thing is to approach the person who's done this to you, you know, and have a little discussion with them.

35
00:03:43,900 --> 00:03:44,961
That's before you hit them.

36
00:03:48,163 --> 00:03:55,114
Now, there's an occasion here where the Buddha is actually, well, abused by somebody.

37
00:03:55,193 --> 00:03:56,975
So I shall read out this little bit.

38
00:03:58,078 --> 00:04:08,652
At one time, the Buddha was staying near Rajagaha in the bamboo grove, the squirrel's feeding ground, and the Brahmin Bharadwaja, the rood,

39
00:04:08,919 --> 00:04:19,471
heard a rumor that a Brahmin of the Bharadvaja clan had gone forth from the lay life to homelessness in the presence of the ascetic Gautama.

40
00:04:19,951 --> 00:04:21,774
So remember that's his family name, Gautama.

41
00:04:22,494 --> 00:04:29,240
Angry and displeased, he went to the Buddha and abused and insulted him with rude and harsh words.

42
00:04:29,742 --> 00:04:34,607
And when he'd spoken, the Buddha said to him, what do you think Brahmin?

43
00:04:34,586 --> 00:04:48,276
do friends and colleagues relatives and family members and guests still come to visit you or sometimes they do master gotama and do you then serve them fresh and cooked foods and savories

44
00:04:48,677 --> 00:04:49,738
Sometimes I do.

45
00:04:49,778 --> 00:04:53,964
And if they don't accept it, Brahmin, who does it belong to?

46
00:04:54,024 --> 00:04:56,749
Well, in that case, it still belongs to me.

47
00:04:56,769 --> 00:05:06,562
In the same way, Brahmin, when you abuse, harass and attack us, who do not abuse, harass and attack, we don't accept it.

48
00:05:06,822 --> 00:05:07,923
It belongs to you.

49
00:05:08,625 --> 00:05:10,466
Brahmin, it still belongs to you.

50
00:05:11,475 --> 00:05:30,632
someone who when abused harassed and attacked abuses harasses and attacks in return is said to eat the food and have a reaction to it but we neither eat your food nor do we have a reaction to it it still belongs to you brahmin it still belongs to you

51
00:05:30,612 --> 00:05:57,091
now the brahmin mistakes the buddha's assertive forthrightness for aggressive uh bluntness and he says ah he says the king and the retinue believe that master gotama is a perfected one and yet he still gets angry so uh one of the signs of somebody who's perfected of course that they they don't get angry or at least when they if they do show anger they're only they're only putting it on

52
00:05:57,072 --> 00:06:23,754
anyway he says the buddha replies for one free of anger tamed living in balance freed with by right understanding one who is composed and at peace where would anger come from when you get angry at an angry person you just make things worse for yourself and when you don't get angry an angry person you win a battle hard to win when you know that the other is angry

53
00:06:24,105 --> 00:06:31,004
You act for the good of both yourself and the other if you're mindful and stay calm.

54
00:06:31,404 --> 00:06:38,502
People unfamiliar with this teaching consider one who heals both oneself and the other to be a fool.

55
00:06:40,423 --> 00:06:48,576
Anyway, this seems to have convinced Bharadvajiv practically bowled over because he then says, oh, excellent Master Gautama.

56
00:06:48,696 --> 00:06:54,184
And before you know it, he's taken refuge in the Buddha to his teaching and to the order.

57
00:06:54,584 --> 00:06:55,867
And he wants to become a monk.

58
00:06:57,848 --> 00:07:02,896
So then he receives the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha's presence.

59
00:07:02,956 --> 00:07:07,122
And not long after the ordination, the Venerable Bharadvajar the Rude,

60
00:07:07,627 --> 00:07:29,870
living alone withdrawn diligent keen and resolute soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life he lived having achieved it with his own insight the goal for which people rightly go forth from lay life into homelessness and he understood

61
00:07:29,935 --> 00:07:31,156
Rebirth has ended.

62
00:07:31,497 --> 00:07:34,021
The spiritual journey has been completed.

63
00:07:34,401 --> 00:07:36,545
What had to be done has been done.

64
00:07:36,906 --> 00:07:40,029
There is no return to any state of becoming.

65
00:07:40,690 --> 00:07:44,276
And the Venerable Bharadwaja became one of the perfected ones.

66
00:07:45,959 --> 00:07:47,742
So I don't know how you handle

67
00:07:48,076 --> 00:07:53,004
when you feel angry about what somebody's done or said about you.

68
00:07:54,807 --> 00:08:03,223
But if somebody has been angry with me, I've learned to just listen to what they say.

69
00:08:03,262 --> 00:08:11,517
Even though there's a reaction here, I put my whole attention on actually what they're saying.

70
00:08:11,649 --> 00:08:22,209
And in so doing, I then reply to what they're saying and maintain at least an outward sign of non-anger, non-reactivity.

71
00:08:22,810 --> 00:08:27,038
And that normally allows them to cool down a bit.

72
00:08:27,259 --> 00:08:31,346
And then hopefully there's some discussion before anything gets worse.

73
00:08:33,250 --> 00:08:37,386
And that leads us, of course, to having patience with others, you know.

74
00:08:37,427 --> 00:08:42,567
Also, you know, we meet people who just get up our noses

75
00:08:42,835 --> 00:08:47,222
And somehow we have to cultivate this acceptance, this patience with them.

76
00:08:48,184 --> 00:08:52,552
So, of course, responding with a certain understanding and compassion.

77
00:08:53,193 --> 00:08:57,923
Now, there was a case at Kanda Bodha, which was where I stayed for quite some time.

78
00:08:58,684 --> 00:09:06,379
A schizophrenic came, at least he told us he'd been diagnosed as a schizophrenic, and he'd obviously stopped taking the pills.

79
00:09:07,118 --> 00:09:14,470
And he was doing some very funny things, like for instance, meditating in the nude, which in the East is a bit off.

80
00:09:15,211 --> 00:09:22,003
And sometimes showering, public showering, you know, where you go to the open well and pour water over yourself.

81
00:09:22,864 --> 00:09:27,051
And he was doing some other silly things that were disturbing people.

82
00:09:27,368 --> 00:09:37,817
So the people there, I didn't know this was going on because the place was sort of a little bit far away from my own hut, you know.

83
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:42,697
And so they went to the abbot and complained about him, you see, but the abbot did nothing.

84
00:09:42,918 --> 00:09:46,163
Eventually, in sort of a bit of desperation, they came to see me.

85
00:09:46,202 --> 00:09:52,653
And I said, well, I said, I'll go up and see the Venerable Upalian and see what he'll do, you know.

86
00:09:53,134 --> 00:09:56,798
So I went up and expressed their annoyance.

87
00:09:57,059 --> 00:10:01,206
Well, the fact that they felt their practice was being heavily disturbed.

88
00:10:01,844 --> 00:10:04,346
And he didn't do anything.

89
00:10:04,587 --> 00:10:14,039
Now, I never knew whether it's because he didn't want to confront this man or whether it was a teaching of just bearing up with what is unpleasant.

90
00:10:14,059 --> 00:10:16,302
And it's usually the unpleasant which disappears.

91
00:10:17,264 --> 00:10:18,245
Usually it's the opposite.

92
00:10:18,326 --> 00:10:21,649
Somebody disturbs you and we tend to move away.

93
00:10:22,250 --> 00:10:26,797
But actually, if you just hang on in there, they usually give up and disappear.

94
00:10:27,477 --> 00:10:29,100
So this was a big teaching for me.

95
00:10:32,253 --> 00:10:38,971
uh the second one of course the other one is endurance in adversity you know when things fall apart

96
00:10:39,559 --> 00:10:50,951
When you have an illness or something like that, or you lose a close friend or a family member, or somebody at work leaves whom you had a good relationship with.

97
00:10:51,633 --> 00:10:58,681
All those things, just the ordinary adversities of life that just come our way, you know, just being able to accept them.

98
00:10:59,241 --> 00:11:00,503
You know, this is the way it is.

99
00:11:00,562 --> 00:11:01,724
That's the big phrase, isn't it?

100
00:11:01,803 --> 00:11:03,306
Just to accept it.

101
00:11:03,285 --> 00:11:22,729
and sometimes i found it helpful to write out the situation so that so that i'm clear as to what's actually happening and that allows this whatever the whatever has arisen anger disappointment grief despair all that sort of stuff it just eventually sort of burns itself out

102
00:11:22,708 --> 00:11:38,811
um i mean as you know recently i had some really bad trouble with um with a with a slipped disc you know which which gave me um which stopped me from walking actually the sciatica and um

103
00:11:39,144 --> 00:11:54,898
Funnily enough, you know, having accepted the situation this year, this is the first time I've actually walked around the meadows twice a day and really sort of enjoyed the way that nature's come alive over the spring.

104
00:11:55,559 --> 00:11:58,065
So it's not been that heavy.

105
00:12:00,205 --> 00:12:04,792
And it all comes down to this basic acceptance, you know, this is the way it is.

106
00:12:04,912 --> 00:12:05,692
This is this.

107
00:12:06,033 --> 00:12:11,942
If you keep saying that to yourself, you know, just sort of banging it into your head, you know, this is the way it is.

108
00:12:12,464 --> 00:12:14,726
And then just letting the heart relax around that.

109
00:12:14,966 --> 00:12:15,648
This is the way it is.

110
00:12:16,168 --> 00:12:18,653
And then the possibilities usually turn up.

111
00:12:20,235 --> 00:12:25,884
I mean, we went through that very strange period of lockdown, you know, that was really weird.

112
00:12:26,745 --> 00:12:31,993
And for many people, it was just an opportunity to do stuff they always wanted to do.

113
00:12:32,052 --> 00:12:33,735
Now they can't do what they usually do.

114
00:12:34,677 --> 00:12:39,764
So take up new hobbies and writing and music and stuff like that.

115
00:12:40,445 --> 00:12:44,149
So it is very much a case of bearing with it.

116
00:12:44,169 --> 00:12:46,352
And it begins with this acceptance, you know.

117
00:12:46,974 --> 00:12:49,618
And then, of course, we find that it's not so bad.

118
00:12:50,206 --> 00:12:56,453
However, there can be situations which are very painful.

119
00:12:57,335 --> 00:13:02,000
And there's a discourse here called the Parable of the Saw.

120
00:13:02,182 --> 00:13:04,544
I'm sure many of you have heard it.

121
00:13:05,285 --> 00:13:17,682
And this is the Buddha says, you know, even with terrible physical pain, monks, even if bandits were to sever you savagely, limb by limb with a two-handed saw,

122
00:13:18,302 --> 00:13:47,549
he who gave rise to a mind of hate towards them would not be carrying out my teachings monks even in such a situation you should train yourselves thus neither shall our minds be affected by this nor for this matter shall we give vent to evil words but we shall remain in full concern and pity with a mind of love and we shall not give in to hatred on the contrary

123
00:13:48,239 --> 00:14:04,900
We shall live projecting thoughts of universal love to those very persons, making them, as well as the whole world, the object of our thoughts of universal love, thoughts that have grown great, exalted, and measureless.

124
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:12,650
We shall dwell radiating these thoughts, which are a void of hostility and ill-will.

125
00:14:12,990 --> 00:14:16,034
In this way you should train yourselves."

126
00:14:16,183 --> 00:14:18,288
That's a bit of a demand, isn't it?

127
00:14:18,669 --> 00:14:24,482
In fact, when I once said this in a talk, somebody said, well, the Buddha had a great sense of humor.

128
00:14:28,130 --> 00:14:34,345
So, you know, bearing up with things just gives us that sense of resilience, you know.

129
00:14:35,961 --> 00:14:44,696
Now, when it comes to our inner practice, I mean, this is also to do with how we react to what's happening to us on the outside.

130
00:14:44,755 --> 00:14:50,926
But of course, it also has an effect of how we react to ourselves within ourselves.

131
00:14:51,246 --> 00:14:56,855
And all this comes under that quality of desire, reaction, reactivity.

132
00:14:56,988 --> 00:15:11,067
And here again, there's an importance to be able to bear with ourselves, you know, to bear with our own thoughts and emotions, sensations and stuff like that, just so that we can develop a clarity of mind.

133
00:15:11,989 --> 00:15:15,533
I was here reminded of Brian Keenan.

134
00:15:15,874 --> 00:15:17,697
Some of you remember this.

135
00:15:17,677 --> 00:15:47,245
so he was uh captured by shiite militiamen um oh i thought i had the date but it goes back a bit 1990 that's when he wrote the book and luckily um he had another person john mccarthy who shared the cell with him and for four years they lived in this really horrible imprisonment state if you read the book evil cradling it really is a shocker and he came out of it

136
00:15:47,292 --> 00:16:14,750
uh from all intents and purposes really strengthened and um i remember when i read the book there's a there's a point there where he has a some sort he has an insight into thought which i thought was uh was a spiritual insight actually uh but unfortunately there was another man there who was an american who really was broken by it it's a sad story

137
00:16:14,730 --> 00:16:24,893
so some people just i mean now we've got this business in uh you know ukraine and russia so there are people having to go this through this sort of stuff

138
00:16:26,087 --> 00:16:31,455
So the final thing is, of course, patience with our spiritual progress.

139
00:16:31,755 --> 00:16:37,864
So you have to be careful here because lots of people say to me, you know, well, I don't feel I'm progressing.

140
00:16:39,566 --> 00:16:44,873
And that means normally that we've got some idea as to where we ought to be.

141
00:16:44,852 --> 00:16:53,702
what we ought to have achieved by now, some idea of what the insight practices are, some idea about nibbani, you see.

142
00:16:54,283 --> 00:17:09,280
So this can be very debilitating and I always think it's best just to put that to the side, you know, because the spiritual practice, so long as you're making that effort, that sort of gentle effort to just keep mindful, keep working with it, it's bound to move.

143
00:17:09,340 --> 00:17:12,243
The Buddha talks of it like the growth of a tree.

144
00:17:12,223 --> 00:17:17,075
you know, from a very seed and how long it takes for that tree to finally fruit.

145
00:17:17,936 --> 00:17:25,776
So it is a case of really having patience with that, but also not getting into it at all, really.

146
00:17:25,875 --> 00:17:27,179
It just happens naturally.

147
00:17:27,199 --> 00:17:30,586
And I think that it's much...

148
00:17:30,719 --> 00:17:43,434
It's much more wise in a way just to work with our negative mental states, because as they begin to lose their power over us, there's a greater clarity anyway.

149
00:17:44,215 --> 00:17:45,457
It's just part of the practice.

150
00:17:49,903 --> 00:17:55,950
In fact, somebody complains to him about how hard the practice is, you see, and the Buddha says, well,

151
00:17:56,200 --> 00:17:58,486
He said, in the end, you achieve Nibbāna.

152
00:17:59,167 --> 00:18:02,636
And the questioner said, yeah, Nibbāna, so what?

153
00:18:03,499 --> 00:18:08,271
He says, well, he says, when you get there, you are happy and with it contented.

154
00:18:09,114 --> 00:18:10,919
Tutti sukha wa hāti.

155
00:18:11,520 --> 00:18:12,403
Tutti frūti.

156
00:18:14,392 --> 00:18:26,647
So we have to be careful about that, not wanting to have some idea as to what spiritual insights or what nibbana is, and just have that sort of confidence that we're moving that way.

157
00:18:29,731 --> 00:18:41,326
So we've been looking at this patient forbearance, which the Buddha sort of really highlights as an important practice, how to work with people who

158
00:18:41,813 --> 00:18:52,396
slander us or abuse us or say nasty things to us have to work with hardships and adversity when it comes our way you know

159
00:18:52,968 --> 00:19:12,036
Cultivating patience towards others and then reactivity either towards others, but spiritually in the practice, this reactivity that we have within ourselves, you know, driven by desire, wanting something, not wanting something, always trying to make the world comfortable.

160
00:19:13,258 --> 00:19:17,545
And then finally, just having patience with the spiritual path.

161
00:19:17,565 --> 00:19:19,768
The Buddha says it's a gradual path.

162
00:19:22,194 --> 00:19:22,736
Very good.

163
00:19:23,838 --> 00:19:37,335
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your development of patient forbearance you will achieve the final liberation from all suffering sooner rather than later.

